<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-464-828  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 464 828.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 21 1990 v24 n21 p97(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'Have I got a system for you!' (sales and marketing systems;includes related articles on the differences between individualmarketing systems, on how computer systems can 'make or break'sales efforts, and on the criteria for adequate informationsystems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mayros, Van.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Marketing information systems (IS) are growing rapidly in mostorganizations as a result of increasing competitive pressures andimproving technology.andP;  A marketing IS is an organized data setmanaged with multiple entries, outputs, and data originationpoints.andP;  Systems in the 1990s will be easy to use and access,offering powerful routines for analyzing statistical data andsuperior presentation tools.andP;  Key trends in Fortune 500 firmsinclude the growth of computer-held information sources; executiveuse of external information and intelligence; and the use ofexternal workstations to capture data directly from customertransactions.andP;  IS can create new data retrieval and manipulationtechniques; existing files often fall short of end-userinformation needs.andP;  Computer conferencing, voice mail andvideoconferencing are methods of providing IS support formarketing systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MarketingSales ManagementManagement of EDP.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Attributes of marketing information systems. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>